T1  - Trading uncertainty and the cash-in-advance constraint
AU  - Eden, Benjamin
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
SP  - 285
EP  - 293
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/11/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(86)90041-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393286900413
AB  - It is argued that when money and bonds are distinct and money yields a lower rate of return, the quantity of private bonds that is exchanged for money is a signal for demand in the near future. Therefore, competitive price setters who observe transactions in the capital market will find it easier to quote prices when money and bonds are distinct relative to the case in which money and bonds are perfect substitutes. In the example analyzed, imposing a cash-in-advance constraint leads to fewer price-setting mistakes and to a Pareto improvement.
ER  - 

