DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(86)90038-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393286900383
AB  - It is widely believed that the U.S. dollar has been high in recent years because of large U.S. budget deficits. Using three statistical techniques, this paper shows that the belief has no empirical support. Ricardian equivalence may explain the lack of a positive association between the budget deficit and the dollar's exchange rate.
